$38M) add-backs more than offset the $(657)M GAAP operating loss. Stripping out Starship R&D as well produces a dramatically different picture, illustrating that the non-GAAP measure is highly sensitive to which costs are allocated to the segment versus excluded via add-backs.\n\n4. **Strategic-investment framing.** Starship is a next-generation platform whose development benefits the entire enterprise (potentially the Connectivity/Starlink and AI segments as well, via launch capacity and cadence). Treating it as a segment cost makes the Space segment look marginally profitable; treating it as a corporate strategic investment would make Space look like a high-margin cash generator. The choice materially affects how investors assess segment-level unit economics and capital allocation.\n\n5. **Disclosure implication.** Because the recast consolidated financials include xAI and X Holdings under common-control accounting, and because Starship R&D is the single largest line item in the Space segment, investors should view Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA as a presentation-dependent metric rather than a clean read on the segment\'s standalone profitability. The filing\'s allocation of Starship R&D to the Space segment is a conservative choice that depresses reported segment profitability relative to an unallocated-corporate treatment.\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Segment Financial Information and Segment Adjusted EBITDA reconciliation"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
